;;; 46-object.slat — Motoi Scheme Reference · Chapter 46 · library object
;;;
;;; 2 verbs in this library. Read chapter 00-intro.slat first.

;;;
;;; ─── THE ROW RULES (summary — full doctrine in 00-intro.slat) ───
;;;
;;; Every verb in this chapter has 5 rows. Each row does ONE job. Row
;;; contamination unbalances training data. If you author or edit a verb,
;;; STAY IN LANE.
;;;
;;;   Row 1 (HOW · Composition) — the verb written well; 1/3/5 module ladder
;;;   Row 2 (WHEN · Audit)      — operator's problem + this-verb-not-a-sibling
;;;   Row 3 (WHERE ELSE · Dim)  — same shape in 3 substrates (verb/metaphor/math)
;;;   Row 4 (WHY · Proof)       — claim + runnable test + ∀-invariant
;;;   Row 5 (WITH WHAT ELSE)    — chained verbs → named emergent pattern
;;;
;;; Every row carries the three-discipline lens: :eng · :math · :cs.
;;; No philosopher names in entries (they live in 00-intro.slat).
;;; Real Motoi domains only (no card/*, shop/*, cine/*, flower/*).
;;; Every code block RUNS through ./bin/motoi (or is marked :runs "spec-only").
;;;
;;; Introspection is a first-class chapter — see 00b-introspection.slat.
;;; Before authoring, run: python3 scripts/audit-reference-rows.py
;;; Before folding, run: python3 scripts/compliance-check-runnable.py
;;;

(dialect :applies ("motoi") :note "Library object — 2 verbs.")

(chapter :number "46" :library "object" :verb-count 2 :training-eligible #t)

;; ═══ 2 verbs in library object ═══

(verb
  :name "object/fetch"
  :library "object"
  :kind "null"
  :signature "(object/fetch [class: ...] [personality: ...] [at: ...] [scale: ...] [colour: ...]) -> 'ok | ['escalate code details]"
  :summary "Retrieve or instantiate an object from the scene, with optional personality and appearance parameters."
  :explanation "Fetches an object resource (likely a pre-defined character, prop, or entity) from the scene or asset library, optionally parameterized by personality vector, position, scale, and colour. Returns 'ok on success, or escalates with a structured error (code, reason, suggestion) if the object cannot be fetched or is not wired. This is a keyword-argument verb; all parameters are optional. Likely useful in imagination/scene-building workflows where you want to populate a scene with named objects on demand."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(object/fetch 'class: 'npc)" :note "Fetches an NPC object from the scene library with default appearance.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(object/fetch 'class: 'npc 'at: (list 10 20) 'scale: 2.0)" :note "Fetches NPC positioned at (10, 20) and scaled to 2× size.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (summon-companion charm wisdom-level)\n  (let ((personality (list charm 0.5 wisdom-level)))\n    (object/fetch 'class: 'companion 'personality: personality 'colour: 'gold)))\n(if (equal? (summon-companion 0.8 0.9) 'ok) (display \"companion ready\") (display \"fetch failed\"))" :note "Higher-order use: encapsulates object fetch with personality vector; checks result before continuing.")
  )
  :caveats ("If class is not registered or wired in the scene, returns escalate with 'not-wired status." "personality should be a list or vector of numeric traits; coercion to exact structure is undocumented." "at and colour parameters are validated but their exact formats are not documented; may require trial." "Success returns only 'ok, not the instantiated object; side effect is scene population.")
  :drawbacks ("No direct return of the spawned object ID; state must be queried separately via card-find-by-kind or card-list." "Requires scene to be pre-wired with object definitions; not suitable for dynamic asset loading." "Error details (reason, suggestion) are for debugging; not suitable for end-user error messages." "Keyword argument order is free but must use valid keys; typos silently become nil.")
  :usecases ("Populating an imagination scene with NPC characters on demand." "Spawning props or objects with custom personality traits (e.g., hostile/friendly)." "Narrative branching: conditionally fetch objects based on game state." "Testing: fetch objects to verify scene wiring and asset availability.")
  :related ("object/spawn" "scene/spawn-many" "scene/load" "card-find-by-kind" "card-list")
  :learn (:concept "Keyword-argument I/O verb for scene population; understanding escalation errors." :prerequisites ("understanding of keyword arguments in Motoi Scheme" "familiarity with escalate error pattern" "understanding of scene wiring and asset registration") :progression "Learn object/spawn to place a specific target; scene/load to pre-populate entire scenes.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A world-builder is prototyping and wants 'some NPC' at (30, 40) — any NPC. They do not have a concrete target ID yet; they only have a class in mind and a rough location. Committing to a specific ID up front is exactly what the prototype phase is trying to avoid."
     :program "(let ((r (object/fetch 'class: 'npc 'at: (list 30 40))))\n  (if (eq? r 'ok)\n    (display \"npc dropped in\")\n    (escalate 'fetch-failed r)))"
     :explanation "The verb accepts a class query rather than a concrete ID, chooses an appropriate object from the class, and drops it into the scene at the requested position. The return is 'ok on success or an escalation triple on failure. The prototype gets to move on with 'an npc is here' without ever naming a specific NPC prefab; the sceneship layer picks the concrete instance."
     :meta "object/spawn requires a concrete target ID and would have forced the world-builder to name a specific NPC prefab, which is the wrong shape for a prototype. scene/spawn-many is for batch stamping a known ID at many positions, not a class query. object/fetch is the query-by-class primitive; using either sibling forces the prototype phase to commit to an ID it does not yet want to pick.")
    (:eng "The audit lens is 'fetch returns 'ok, not an ID' — the operator does not get a handle to the spawned object and must query the scene separately if they need one; log-checking that a spawn happened requires reading the scene state, not the return value." :math "The verb is a class-indexed picker: fetch : Class → Instance, non-deterministic within the class; the operator receives a status, not the picked element." :cs "Non-deterministic constructor / factory-by-tag pattern; the same shape as 'give me any file from this directory' vs 'give me this specific file'."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Class-indexed acquisition: request 'one of these' rather than 'this specific one'."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "object"       :code "(object/fetch 'class: 'npc)")
       (:domain "worker-pool"  :code "(define (lease pool) (car pool))\n(lease '(worker-1 worker-2 worker-3))")
       (:domain "existential"  :code "(define (any-of xs pred) (cond ((null? xs) #f) ((pred (car xs)) (car xs)) (else (any-of (cdr xs) pred))))\n(any-of '(1 2 3 4) even?)"))
     :explanation "Rung 1: a scene is asked for an instance of a class rather than a specific object. Rung 2: a worker pool is asked to lease a worker, and the pool chooses any available one. Rung 3: an existential quantifier says 'there exists some x such that pred(x) holds'; the return is a witness, not a name the caller had to know. All three share the same shape — a request specifies a set, the substrate picks a member, and the picked member need not be named by the caller."
     :meta "The transfer works because 'class query' is really 'existential ask' — the caller does not know or care which instance answers, only that the set is non-empty and something in it works. Worker pools, DNS round-robin, and DHCP leases all use the shape; class-fetch is the same primitive in a scene substrate. Grounds in book-of-code ch 16 (cloud-llms-and-the-loop-that-closes) as the request-a-worker shape.")
     (:eng "The audit lens is 'the picked instance is not named in the return so the operator cannot log 'which one' from the call site' — every class-picker needs a companion introspection call if forensics is needed later." :math "Existential witness: ∃ x ∈ Class. spawn(x) holds; the substrate provides the witness but does not surface it in the return channel." :cs "Non-deterministic factory; classic pool-lease pattern where the caller has policy 'any member' and the pool has strategy 'pick something'."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "The picked instance carries the requested class: every successful fetch places an object whose class matches the query."
     :program "(define scene '())\n(define registry '((npc . (npc-warrior npc-scholar npc-child))\n                   (prop . (chair table lantern))))\n(define (fetch class-tag)\n  (let ((entries (assq class-tag registry)))\n    (if entries\n      (let ((pick (car (cdr entries))))\n        (set! scene (cons (list class-tag pick) scene))\n        'ok)\n      (escalate 'unknown-class class-tag))))\n(fetch 'npc)\n(fetch 'prop)\n(fetch 'npc)\n(define (every p xs) (cond ((null? xs) #t) ((p (car xs)) (every p (cdr xs))) (else #f)))\n(display (every (lambda (row) (assq (car row) registry)) scene))"
     :invariant "∀ class. fetch(class) succeeds ⇒ scene contains an object whose class = class  (soundness of the class-tag on the picked instance)"
     :meta "The CS pattern is soundness — the returned witness must actually satisfy the query. Falsified if a fetch for 'npc placed a chair — that would mean the picker is lying and the caller can no longer trust class as a contract. book-of-code ch 05 (logic-gates-in-scheme) grounds the every-predicate check; book-of-math ch-advanced-05 grounds the well-typed-picker shape.")
    (:eng "The engineering consequence is that a caller filtering the scene by class after a fetch will find at least one entry — 'I asked for an npc and I can find an npc' is the audit check that catches picker regressions." :math "The picker is a section of the class projection: pick : Class → Instance with class(pick(c)) = c." :cs "Well-typed factory; the type of the picked value is exactly the class-tag, and this is enforced structurally."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "object/fetch instantiates an object of a queried class at an optional position."
     :composition "(define (populate-market classes)\n  (for-each\n    (lambda (c)\n      (let ((r (object/fetch 'class: c 'at: (list (random-range 10 90)\n                                                   (random-range 10 90)))))\n        (if (not (eq? r 'ok))\n          (escalate 'populate-skip (list c r)))))\n    classes))\n(populate-market '(vendor customer guard child dog))\n(display (group/count 'npc))"
     :emergent "A crowd populator: a class list is walked, each class-fetch drops an instance at a random cell, and the aggregate scene has a distribution of NPC types matching the class list; together they are a distribution-generator, structurally the same as sampling from a categorical distribution."
     :meta "This is the population / sampler family — a class-tag list defines the distribution, and per-class fetch draws one sample per tag. Familiar analogs are Poisson process spawners in games, monte-carlo samplers in statistics, and the categorical sampler in a numpy simulation. The composition works because each fetch is a class-safe pick (Row 4) so the emergent distribution over the scene actually matches the intended distribution over classes. Grounds in book-of-math ch-advanced-07 (probability-random-processes) as the categorical-sampling shape.")
    (:eng "The audit lens: partial failure of any single class must not silently vanish; the escalate captures the class-and-reason so the operator can tell which classes were rejected by the picker and rebalance the target distribution." :math "The composition is a fold over the class list with each step being an existential-choice; the joint distribution factors as the product of per-tag choices when picks are independent." :cs "Categorical sampler; the same shape as populating a hash table from a list of keys with any-value-of-type semantics.")))

(verb
  :name "object/spawn"
  :library "object"
  :kind "null"
  :signature "(object/spawn target [at: ...] [scale: ...] [colour: ...]) -> 'ok | ['escalate code details]"
  :summary "Instantiate a named object into the current scene at an optional position, scale, and colour."
  :explanation "Spawns a specific object (identified by the target symbol or identifier) into the scene with optional appearance and placement parameters. Like object/fetch, returns 'ok on success or escalates with code and details on failure (e.g., target not found or not wired). The key difference from object/fetch is that object/spawn takes a concrete target identifier rather than a class query. Useful for placing individual prefabs, enemies, or props in scene setup or dynamic game events."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(object/spawn 'sword-pickup)" :note "Spawns a named object 'sword-pickup' at default position.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(object/spawn 'enemy-guard 'at: (list 50 60) 'scale: 1.5)" :note "Spawns 'enemy-guard' at position (50, 60) scaled 1.5×.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (populate-treasure-room treasure-ids)\n  (for-each\n    (lambda (id)\n      (let ((result (object/spawn id 'at: (list (random-range 20 80) (random-range 20 80)))))\n        (if (pair? result) (escalate 'spawn-failed (list 'id id)))))\n    treasure-ids))\n(populate-treasure-room (list 'gold-coin 'gem 'potion))" :note "Batch spawn multiple objects at random positions; escalate if any fail.")
  )
  :caveats ("target must be a registered object ID; typos or non-existent IDs escalate with 'not-wired." "No return of instantiated object; must query separately via card-find-by-kind or card-list." "colour parameter format is undocumented; may be a symbol or hex string." "Spawning at out-of-bounds coordinates may cause undefined behavior.")
  :drawbacks ("Synchronous and blocking; no async spawn queue for many objects." "No way to configure post-spawn state (HP, team, etc.) directly; requires follow-up card-set! calls." "Error does not include spawned object ID on success; caller must track separately." "Repeated calls with same target/position may cause collision or overlap; no deduplication.")
  :usecases ("Procedural level generation: spawn enemies and props at computed positions." "Cutscene scripting: spawn characters or objects in narrative sequences." "Dynamic events: spawn rewards, hazards, or NPCs in response to player action." "Testing: verify that all registered objects can be instantiated.")
  :related ("object/fetch" "scene/spawn-many" "scene/load" "card-set!" "world/spawn")
  :learn (:concept "Direct object instantiation; keyword parameters for appearance; escalation error handling." :prerequisites ("understanding of keyword arguments" "understanding of escalate and error tuples" "familiarity with object/fetch") :progression "Learn scene/spawn-many for batch spawning; world/spawn for physics entities.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A level designer knows exactly which asset to place — 'enemy-guard-heavy' — and needs it at (50, 60) with 1.5× scale, not any old NPC. A class query would pick some enemy but the designer already picked; asking again would be redundant and possibly wrong."
     :program "(let ((r (object/spawn 'enemy-guard-heavy 'at: (list 50 60) 'scale: 1.5)))\n  (if (eq? r 'ok)\n    (display \"guard placed\")\n    (escalate 'guard-not-wired r)))"
     :explanation "The verb accepts a concrete target ID, positions the spawned instance at (50, 60), and scales it to 1.5×. 'ok on success; an escalation triple on failure. The designer's intent — 'this exact prefab, here, at this size' — is preserved end-to-end; no class picker gets a chance to substitute."
     :meta "object/fetch would let the scene pick some NPC and defeat the designer's specificity; scene/spawn-many is for stamping the same target at many positions, not a single-shot placement. object/spawn is the by-name primitive; picking either sibling either loses the designer's chosen ID or does the wrong quantity.")
    (:eng "The audit lens is 'the target ID appears verbatim in the escalation payload on failure' — if the ID is missing from the payload, the designer cannot tell whether they typoed the ID or the prefab is broken; the SRE check is grep-for-target-id in the log." :math "spawn is a total function from (target-id ∈ registry) × Position × Scale → SceneState, with domain guarded by the registry-membership predicate." :cs "Deterministic factory / by-name constructor; the same shape as new ClassName() in an OO language."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "By-name placement: request a specific member of a registry at a specific location."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "object"     :code "(object/spawn 'enemy-guard 'at: (list 50 60))")
       (:domain "process"    :code "(define (spawn cmd) (display cmd) 'started)\n(spawn \"nginx\")")
       (:domain "function-application" :code "(define (apply-at f x) (f x))\n(apply-at (lambda (v) (* 2 v)) 10)"))
     :explanation "Rung 1: a scene is asked to place a specifically-named prefab at a specific coordinate. Rung 2: a shell is asked to spawn a specifically-named binary; the OS looks up the name and executes it. Rung 3: a function is applied at a specific argument, producing a specific value. All three share the same shape — a named thing is invoked at a named place, and the substrate produces one concrete outcome; the caller specified everything and the substrate has no picking to do."
     :meta "The transfer works because 'by-name' is the total-function shape: given a legal name and its input, the output is uniquely determined. This is the shape of every deterministic factory and it stands in contrast to the class-picker of object/fetch. Grounds in book-of-code ch 12 (the-cpu-fetch-decode-execute) as the by-address fetch shape.")
     (:eng "Every by-name substrate has the same failure mode — 'name not in registry' — and the SRE fix is 'preflight the name against the registry before the call' so the substrate's error surface is bounded." :math "Function application at a specific argument; the caller lives in the domain and the substrate produces a value in the codomain, deterministically." :cs "Named-entity registry; the shape of DNS A-records, symbol tables, and prefab dictionaries."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "Spawn is location-honest: the spawned object's position equals the requested position."
     :program "(define scene '())\n(define registry '(chest coin gem))\n(define (spawn target at)\n  (if (memv target registry)\n    (begin (set! scene (cons (list target at) scene)) 'ok)\n    (list 'escalate 'not-wired target)))\n(spawn 'chest '(10 20))\n(spawn 'coin '(30 40))\n(define (every p xs) (cond ((null? xs) #t) ((p (car xs)) (every p (cdr xs))) (else #f)))\n(display (every (lambda (row) (equal? (cadr row) (cadr row))) scene)) (newline)\n(display (equal? (cadr (assq 'chest scene)) '(10 20)))"
     :invariant "∀ target position. spawn(target, position) = 'ok ⇒ scene contains (target, position)  (the position argument is preserved into the scene state)"
     :meta "The CS pattern is faithful storage — the caller's input coordinate must appear verbatim in the state, unaltered by the substrate. Falsified if the substrate rounded, clamped, or otherwise moved the coordinate silently — that would mean 'at:' is a suggestion, not a contract, and the designer's layout would drift under them. book-of-code ch 08 (memory-latches-and-flip-flops) grounds the faithful-write shape; book-of-math ch-advanced-04 grounds identity-preservation.")
    (:eng "The engineering consequence is that a designer inspecting the scene state after a spawn will see the same coordinate they typed; QA can round-trip a spec from JSON into the world without pixel drift." :math "The (target, position) argument tuple is preserved by the write — the substrate is a faithful embedding of the API call into the state graph." :cs "Faithful setter / write-through; the same shape as an in-memory store where set(k,v) then get(k) returns v exactly."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "object/spawn places a named target at a coordinate."
     :composition "(define (formation origin count spacing target)\n  (let loop ((i 0) (fails 0))\n    (if (>= i count)\n      (if (> fails 0) (escalate 'formation-partial fails) 'ok)\n      (let* ((x (+ (car origin) (* i spacing)))\n             (y (cadr origin))\n             (r (object/spawn target 'at: (list x y))))\n        (loop (+ i 1) (if (eq? r 'ok) fails (+ fails 1)))))))\n(formation '(20 40) 5 12 'grenadier)"
     :emergent "A formation composer: an origin and spacing plus a target ID plus a count generate a line-abreast of instances; together they are a placement pattern generator, structurally the same as a tile-map row-generator or a for-loop mail-merge that reuses a template."
     :meta "This is the templating / batch-instantiation family — one template, N derived placements, aggregated result. Familiar analogs are HTML template loops, DDL scripts that CREATE TABLE many times from a schema list, and Kubernetes replicasets that spawn N identical pods. The composition works because spawn is location-honest (Row 4) so the caller's arithmetic on x-positions arrives at the scene exactly — the formation looks like the math predicted. Grounds in book-of-sick-composition ch 4 (recursion) as the count-driven loop shape.")
    (:eng "Partial-failure aggregation is the SRE lens: the loop counts fails and returns an escalation summarizing them, so the operator learns that 3 of 5 spawns worked and can adjust the target inventory instead of chasing a single-shot error." :math "The composition is a fold over the position schedule; success count and fail count are the two accumulators tracked by the fold." :cs "Batch-with-partial-failure; the shape of every bulk-insert API that returns per-row status.")))
